deI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="genv"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Natural Environment</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gclimt"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gglobe"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Global/World Issues</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gclimt"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Companies &amp; Markets</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">HOCK LOCK SIEW; Local banks need to match S'pore's green push</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>AS Singapore designates 2018 to be the Year of Climate Action, there has been much talk about how the country can play a role in leading the fight against climate change. The government has received some 70,000 pledges, including some by companies pledging to reduce the use of paper cups.</Para><Para>The real lever of change in this movement, however, lies with the financial sector - one that has influence beyond the island-state. It is therefore no surprise that the three local banks have received scrutiny in recent months for the loans they have extended to coal projects in the region.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Australian environmental advocacy group Market Forces in late January released a study claiming that DBS Bank, OCBC and UOB have financed 21 coal project deals since 2012 worth US$2.29 billion. More than half of these were for coal-fired power stations, mainly in Indonesia and Vietnam, it said.</Para><Para>The banks have not contested these numbers. In response, however, they said the financing of these projects helps local communities gain access to electricity; they also pointed out that developing countries in the region are dependent on coal as part of their energy mix to deliver economic growth.</Para><Para>Market Forces' rebuttal to their argument: with renewable energy being cheaper than coal in many countries, there is no longer any need for coal.</Para><Para>In this renewables-versus-coal debate, it is easy to miss the bigger picture. With renewables such as solar and wind producing intermittent power, there is still a need for baseload power plants which can keep the lights on - even when the sun isn't shining, and the wind isn't blowing.</Para><Para>While several countries in Europe have successfully incorporated renewables on a large scale into their energy mix, this has only been possible because of an interconnected grid which allows them to sell or buy electricity from one another when the need arises.</Para><Para>In Southeast Asia, such a grid is not yet in existence. While the idea has been discussed for decades, it remains very much a long-term vision, though various bilateral interconnections have been put in place.</Para><Para>In the absence of an Asean grid and grid-wide battery storage, both old and new energy systems would have to co-exist in this energy transition, probably for decades to come. How both can do so is a question that would have to be addressed by energy regulators in each jurisdiction.</Para><Para>Banks, however, still have a critical role to play. In deciding what to support, they can nudge project developers toward the most efficient coal plants, if indeed such coal plants have better economics than other types of power generation.</Para><Para>Setting limits</Para><Para>In this, the first step would be for banks to set clear limits on what they would fund, or not. Standard Chartered, for instance, has said it would not provide financing to new coal-fired power plants which have a long-emissions intensity of above 830 gram of carbon emissions for each kilowatt hour of electricity generated. For ANZ Bank, the limit is 800 gram. None of the local banks have publicly specified such limits.</Para><Para>Banks also have to ensure that they are involved in renewable project deals that make economic sense, especially as renewable power generation technologies increasingly become competitive with conventional fuels.</Para><Para>To be sure, DBS, in its annual report published on Wednesday, revealed that it has arranged financing for geothermal energy projects in Indonesia and wind farms in Australia.</Para><Para>It has also extended one billion yuan (S$208 million) in bilateral financing to CPI Leasing, part of China's top five state-owned electricity producer State Power Investment Corporation Group. CPI Leasing is involved in renewable energy for close to three quarters of its leasing exposure, DBS said.</Para><Para>As a financial hub, however, Singapore's banks will be expected to do even more, especially in spearheading innovation in sustainable finance.</Para><Para>In this vein, there have been encouraging moves by banks, albeit foreign ones, to create in Singapore new types of financing instruments tied to sustainability targets, though these are in a different sector.</Para><Para>Dutch Bank ING, for instance, has agreed to reduce the interest rate on part of an existing credit facility for Wilmar International if the latter hits certain environmental, social and governance (ESG) targets, including the reduction of greenhouse emissions.</Para><Para>Olam International on Monday also said it has secured a three-year US$500 million revolving credit facility in which the interest rate will be reduced if annual ESG targets are met. ING Bank is the sustainability co-ordinator for the facility, while BNP Paribas is the facility agent.</Para><Para>As the world's energy sector evolves, the three Singapore banks will not only have to keep up. They will also be expected to match the country's rhetoric in leading the charge against climate change.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Andrea Soh , Local banks need to match S'pore's green push </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

